Preheat your #oven{} to 200°C. Pop the @diced butternut squash{300%g} onto a #roasting tray{}, drizzle over the @oil{} and season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Roast until tender and turning golden, ~{15-20%minutes}.

Halve, peel and thinly slice the @onion{1}(peeled and thinly sliced). Peel and grate the @garlic{2%cloves}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}). Drain and rinse the @chickpeas{1%400g can}. Heat a drizzle of oil in a large #saucepan{} over medium heat and cook the onion until softened, ~{6-8%minutes}. Add the garlic and @harissa paste{50%g} and cook for a further ~{1%minute}.

Add the @water{150%ml} and @vegetable stock powder{1} to the onion and bring to a simmer. Stir to dissolve and cook until reduced slightly, ~{5-6%minutes}. Meanwhile, crumble the @feta cheese{100%g} into chunks.

Add the @baby spinach{125%g} to the saucepan a handful at a time and stir until it has all wilted, ~{2-3%minutes}. Stir through the chickpeas, feta and cooked butternut squash. Taste and add more salt and pepper if you like.

Transfer the butternut squash mixture to an ovenproof #dish{} (we use a 20cm x 20cm dish for 2 people). Unroll the @puff pastry sheet{1} and place on top of the butternut mixture to cover and turn into a pie. Using a #fork{}, press the pastry over the edge of the dish to help seal. Trim away any excess pastry and cut a small hole in the centre with the tip of a #knife{}. Transfer the pie to the top shelf of your oven. Bake until the pastry is golden and well risen, ~{15-20%minutes}.

While the pie is in the oven, do any washing up. Once cooked, leave the pie to stand for ~{2%minutes} then divide between plates. Enjoy!

> We love a good Harissa Butternut and Chickpea Pie and this deliciously simple, chef-curated recipe doesn't disappoint. Time to bust out the pots and pans!